<font color="#FF0000">LIMPID SPARROW</font><br>
<tt>Mon Sep 22  1:19:31 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Ed, <br>
You shared the podium with an active duty Master Gunnery Sergeant, what's the Corps coming to? I hope you stood at attention and bowed in reverance, I'm amazed you were able to stand after having been so honored.<br><br>
In regards to what I said before, it had to do with training, I did not mean to say that Marines were not effected as others serving in Nam were, I was jsut wondering about the time period in which we served, 67-68. It was the best of times and it was the worst of times, etc. The same would apply to all servicemen in Nam during that time, though Green Berets were just happy to have gotten just another medal or patch.<br><br>
Up until recently, I hadn't given my Vietnam experience much time, I had not taken the time for reflection and this has all been a new experience for me. Reminds me of Keeton when he was medivacked from the field. There he was on the chopper bleeding from having been shot, but worried about the guys still shooting it out below and feeling guilty about leaving before the job was done. <br>
Perhaps that's the guilt I feel, of a job never accomplished, I've never felt that we lost the war, I felt that we failed to help the South Vietnamese keep their country. <br>
Sometimes you feel like you weren't issued all your equipment, It's a corps thing. You may not need it or want to carry another thing in your back pack but you just want an answer as to why you weren't issued PTSD like some of the other branches of government, or somebody else in another Marine company or platoon. I guess, if the corps wanted us to have PTSD they would have issued it to us. <br>
That's what I mean by saying that marine training may have had a lot to do with it.<br>
I recall a few times in the open rice paddies trying to drag scared Marines out of the kill zones, but they were too focused on the danger surrounding them to respond. Too closely associating with the negative to realize the danger they were in.<br>
I was too afraid to think about what was going on, because I feared fear. Feared I would let others down.<br>
Found myself concentrating on getting those out in the open out of the danger zones and that took the fear away. Dismissed it after that never bothered to think back about what happened. <br>
It was all part of that Marine Corps training.<br>
On the Rifle range at boot camp we would shoot until we qualified, humped until we overcame. Learned how to breathe, sight in, adjust and squeeze. Learned how to keep going after your body said NO more. Tore you apart, the fear of not qualifying, of not keeping up with the others, of letting others down, you were a Marine, you volunteered, you better not fail.<br>
But once we qualified, accomplished our mission, the whole platoon moved on, those that didn't make it were left behind, to be picked up by another boot unit, picking up recycled Marines. <br>
Afterwards, the D.I. would always tell us, after we completed extra ordinary events that tore you apart in mind, body and soul. <br>
'O.K. that's over now. You are not to think about it again. It's over, it's past. You are a Marine that has completed that part of your training. There's more up ahead, but you've accomplished that task, so forget about it. You are not to look back, it's over.&quot;<br>
We never looked back in Nam, never talked about what we had experienced, during the battle scenes. Never talked about what we had accomplished, never spoke about the pain, suffering, we simply dismissed a comrade's absence with silence. I'm not too sure that it was the same for other Marine units, I can only relate to those I served with. Perhaps in the next newsletter I'll run a survey and asked for their comments on the subject. It should bring back some interesting results.<br><br>
P.S.<br>
I'll join you in the PTSD tread as soon as I figure out what you said. I'll need to get out my secret decorder ring out, or read it in the morning when my minds alert. <br>

<p><code>-- USMC  (Sparrowhawk) </code><p>


